Use a classical decomposition to calculate the trend-cycle and seasonal indices.

  1. Do the results support the graphical interpretation from part (a)? yes it does because we start with a downward tred and go up on the first two parts. The third one is a perfectly seasonally adjusted trend. The fourth one identifies random walk

  2. Compute and plot the seasonally adjusted data.

  3. Change one observation to be an outlier (e.g., add 500 to one observation), and recompute the seasonally adjusted data. What is the effect of the outlier? The outlier creates a spike in the plot.

  1. Does it make any difference if the outlier is near the end rather than in the middle of the time series? yes it makes a difference during decomposition the trend flattens out on first display and last display
